[[Image:Paul Jamin - Le Brenn et sa part de butin 1893.jpg|thumb|right|260px|"''Le Brenn et sa part de butin''" ("Brenn and His Share of the Spoils"), painting by Paul Jamin (1893), Musée des beaux-arts de La Rochelle.]] '''Paul Joseph Jamin''' (9 February 1853 – 10 July 1903) was a [[French people|French]] [[Painting|painter]] of the [[Academic Classicism]] school.
==Life and career== Jamin was born in [[Paris]] in 1853.<ref name="Bryan">{{Cite book |title=Bryan's dictionary of painters and engravers |volume=III |last=Bryan |first=Michael |author2=George Charles Williamson |authorlink=Michael Bryan (art historian) |year=1904 |publisher=George Bell & sons |location=London |isbn= |oclc=557491136 |page=105 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RMZHAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA105 }}</ref> He was the son of [[Jules Jamin]], renowned physicist and permanent secretary of the [[French Academy of Sciences]].<ref name="Bryan"/> He married Augustine Marie Caroline Bastien in 1882, with whom he had four children.
His paintings were shown frequently at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] throughout the last quarter of the nineteenth century.<ref name="Bryan"/> One of his best-known paintings is ''Le Brenn et sa part de butin'' (1893), which depicts the barbarian chieftain [[Brennus (4th century BC)|Brennus]] viewing his captives after the looting of [[Ancient Rome|Rome]].
Jamin died in Paris on 10 July 1903.<ref name="Bryan"/>
